  					<td align=center valign="top" width=100%><br>
  						<!--#beginContent#-->
  						<table align='center' cellpadding=5 width='85%'>  <tr><td class='spti2' width='100%'>PLAYER STRATEGY - CLERIC</td></tr>  <tr><td width='100%' class='db'><font class='dbti'>CLASS BY CLASS GUIDE TO DUELING OTHER PC'S</font> - <small>Eilar Everheal, Fennin Ro</td></tr>
  <tr><td width='100%' class='db'><p>Ok most people tell you to always have your two invulnerable
spells mem'ed at all times. The divine aura line of spells is
great, don't get me wrong, but they take up two valuable spell
slots and when you cast them you cant really do anything usefull
but med and then only that for a short amount of time. Now
against most casters, clerics are a major pain in the ass because
of our stun line of spells but against melee types we dont really
have too much of a chance. I'll start off with what we are good
at but as a cleric with arguably the best buffs in the game
remember to always buff yourself according to your opponents
strengths.<br>
Wizards: The masters of direct damage. They usually start off
with their two stun spells and then start casting ice comet or
snare and either keep doing the stun/ice comet combo or use
stun/and some fire based dd that I couldnt tell what it was. You
should cast resist fire, cold, magic, resolution, armor of faith,
and armor of protection upon yourself before the fight. This
strategy will prove usefull against many casters of all classes,
lead with that lvl 5 stun spell. That spell costs so little and
is hardly ever resisted. Follow with force and then cast
retribution on the wizzie. If your stun spells are not sticking
dont panic, retribution will most likely still hit for good
amounts of dmg but keep trying the stuns to interupt his casts.
Also cleric's melee sucks...but it does have its uses. Get in
melee range and try to beat on that wizzie, they can yaw and
shadow step but it will cost them mana. Just keep nuking and cast
greater healing on yourself a couple times through the fight, no
need to waste 250 mana on superior healing when we dont have that
many hp's.<br>
Shaman: Master debuffers, dot'ers, and buffers. Cast resist
poison, disease, cold, magic, and all hp/ac buffs on yourself
first. They will usually try to land a debuff spell first, either
nullifying your buffs or a malosi type spell, and send pet in.
Ignore the shaman for a moment and lets concentrate on the pet.
It can't cast so if you root it you dont have to worry about
getting nuked like a mage pet would do, if you fear it it is also
going to get out of the way. Use either strategy and turn
attention back to the shaman. By now the shaman has probably
stacked some poison or disease based dot on you and is casting
his cold based nuke. If you buffed up your resistances he
probably has spent alot of mana getting those dot's to stick, and
his cold based nuke probably won't hit for full. Cast root on him
so he doesnt try to kite you around letting his dots work and
keeping you from casting. Then he has to go toe to toe with you
and his nukes suck compared to yours, just cast retribution, lvl
5 stun spell, greater heal on yourself, stun, nuke and keep up
till hes dead.<br>
Enchanter....well You say 'My leader is &lt;place enchanter's
name here&gt;.' Use all of your stun spells, and your nukes. Buff
up magic resists and your hp/ac buffs. If you dont buff up magic
you will have negative save vs magic when he casts the tashani
line of spells on you. Stun at every chance you get, nuke after
stuns, get in melee range and beat as much as possible on him to
interupt him. Usually the enchanter will win though, you will
have 0 mana after he steals it all, 0 magic resistance after he
debuffs you, and you will be made to run at monsters like his
pet.<br>
Druids: you have all seen them kite around a mob till its
dead....dont be that mob. Buff up resistances against fire, cold,
magic hp/ac buffs. Lead fight with stun, then holy might, then
force, then retribution. The druid will eventually land a snare,
the insect dot, and start running away. DO NOT FOLLOW!! Run the
other way, they will realize you are out of range and come back
to start casting a nuke, when you see them cast start stuning or
rooting. Force them to stand still, if they do they are dead.
Also do not melee a druid, they have dmg shields on that do so
much more dmg to you then you are doing to them, if you are oom
have furor mem'ed, it does around 19 dmg wich is more then your
melee and it only costs like 30 mana. Use stuns and nukes and
keep meleeing them till they die.<br>
<br>
Mages: Weak wizards accompanied by a monstrous tank. Buff
resistances of fire and magic, then hp/ac buffs. Target pet and
either root and run out of its range or fear it. If you can get
the pet out of the way you have won. If not you are dead, there
is no inbetween with mages. Once pet is out of the way nuke and
stun the mage using melee as an interupt. When pet comes back
start fearing or rooting to keep it away. You will either lose
horribly or win easily with them there is no inbetween...usually
the first one.<br>
Necromancers: Unreal dot's and an undead warrior to help them.
Buff every resistance except cold and fire, target the necro
first not the pet. Lead with the lvl 9 stun spell on the necro
then target pet, root it and back off. He cant fear kite you
without a pet. When the fear spell that the necro just cast on
you while you were messing with his pet wears off or if it doesnt
stick run back to the necro and try to melee, make him shadow
step and yaw to burn mana. use stuns everytime he casts and keep
nuking him. Remember if he dies the pet does too so keep at him
as hard as you can. Remembering to back up and greater heal
yourself as needed with the dot's ticking away at you.<br>
Clerics: Master buffers, rely heavily on one or two lines of
spells. Buff magic resistance and hp/ac buffs. Lead fight with
lvl 9 stun spell, then nullify magic once or twice to get rid of
his buffs. Use stun and nuke if you need to med, use fear not
root.<br>
Melee classes: you will die fast, they will have lots of hp's
left. EXCEPT rangers, monks, and rogues.<br>
Rangers: Druids with melee. Use the exact same strategy you did
with the druid. They will usually try to melee and use their high
dmg to their advantage, root or fear him in that case. Dont
bother with stuns except to help get root or fear off. Keep
nuking and root/fearing till hes dead.<br>
<br>
Monks: Amazingly fast high damage dealers. Dont bother with stuns
to get your root off, the root has less resistance checks then
the stun does. Keep casting root till you finally 'regain your
concentration and keep casting' back up, heal yourself, nuke him
till root wears off, back up root again. When root sticks, run to
the limit of how far you can cast on him and then nuke, if root
breaks you will have time to recast it before he hits you. Beware
of mend, there is no way you can stop his healing himself. Also
when you get him to half life he will begin bandaging himself
keep nuking, even if its only the smite spell or furor.<br>
Rogues: They do very very high damage....if you turn your back.
Blind him at the outset. They will try to hide/sneak around
behind you to backstab or instill doubt to make you run away
while they backstab. Most important thing to remember is to keep
either root or flash of light on them at all times. Keep nuking
and recasting flash of light when it wears off. Root is good but
it breaks when you hit for full dmg usually and it costs more
mana. Use whichever you prefer.<br>
<br>
</p>
</td></tr>
